==劇情==
===Background===
The episode begins with Finn having a dream about the Lich-possessed snail using the Enchiridion to attack Billy. Finn then wakes up and tells Jake about his dream, who—after hearing that the Cosmic Owl appeared in the dream—believes it is a premonition. The two go visit Billy, and tell him about the dream. Billy realizes the importance of the dream, and the three of them set out to stop the Lich. After they head out, Billy tells them that they need to collect all the magical gems from all the princesses and Ice King's power crystals that protect them from the Lich. With only one gem left, Finn finds the Enchiridion in Billy's knapsack. Billy reveals that the book has magical properties, and after activating it a certain way, the circle on the front opens up showing 9 slots where all the gems go in, and it shows a brief diagram about what would happen if all the slots where filled.

A holographic being named Booko appears and explains that when all the gems are placed in the book, a portal to the [[multiverse|multiverse]] will be opened. Billy claims that he is going to throw the Lich through this portal. Finn and Jake then set off to get the last gem: Princess Bubblegum's. Finn and Jake try to take the gem, a scuffle ensues, and the duo manages to get the gem. Once outside, Finn puts the gem in the final slot. Lights start to flash out of the stones on book. Then the book starts to shake while the pieces start to fall off as the Enchiridion turns into a black block. As Finn is running, Billy tells Finn to hurry. Princess Bubblegum then runs out telling Finn that Billy is really the Lich.

Just as she says this, one of the Gumball Guardians gets up, detecting the Lich, and blasts Billy revealing that half of Billy's face is actually the Lich's. The Lich then asks for the book, but Finn smashes the book with his knee. However, his action accidentally opens up a wormhole. The Lich tries to pass through but Jake grabs him. Finn and Jake then try to stop him from going through, but are inevitably pulled through. The scene dramatically changes; Finn—in a completely different art style—is playing his flute with Jake, who appears to be a regular, non-talking dog. The two are sitting outside a small house with a barn next to it. His mother calls him in for what she says is "something important," and the episode ends with Finn assuming he has done something wrong and he and Jake quickly run inside.

==Production==
[[Image:WLA_metmuseum_1495_Unicorn_captivity.jpg|thumb]]
"The Lich" was written by Tom Herpich and Skyler Page, from a story by [[Patrick_McHale_(cartoonist)|Patrick McHale]], [[Kent_Osborne|Kent Osborne]], and [[Pendleton_Ward|Pendleton Ward]]. It was directed by [[Larry_Leichliter|Larry Leichliter]].<ref name=lichep>{{cite episode| title=The Lich| series=Adventure Time| serieslink=|credits = Larry Leichliter (director); Tom Herpich & Skyler Page (writers) | network = [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] |airdate=October 22, 2012 | season = 4 | number = 26}}</ref> The episode guest stars [[Lou_Ferrigno|Lou Ferrigno]] as the hero Billy, and [[Ron_Perlman|Ron Perlman]] as the Lich.<ref name=lichep/> Ferrigno had previously appeared in the [[Adventure_Time_(season_1)|first season]] episode "His Hero", and Perlman had previously appeared in the [[Adventure_Time_(season_2)|second season]] entry "Mortal Recoil".<ref name=voiceactors1>{{cite web|last=Stopera|first=Dave|title=25 Actors You Might Not Have Known Did Voices On 'Adventure Time'|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/daves4/25-actors-you-might-not-have-known-did-voices-on|work=[[BuzzFeed|BuzzFeed]]|publisher=BuzzFeed Inc|accessdate=January 14, 2013|year=2012|archive-date=2015-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517025627/http://www.buzzfeed.com/daves4/25-actors-you-might-not-have-known-did-voices-on|dead-url=no}}</ref>

In the opening scene, Herpich used unicorn symbolism, most notable the tapestry ''The Unicorn is in Captivity and No Longer Dead'', a piece of the seven-part tapestry ''[[The_Hunt_of_the_Unicorn|The Hunt of the Unicorn]]'', to illustrate the themes of the episode.<ref name=storyboard/><ref name=ristaino/> According to then-character designer Andy Ristaino, the decision was conscientious, but that "as for the meaning you're just going to have to think about unicorn symbology and how that relates to a specific character in the episode."<ref name=ristaino>{{cite web|last=Ristaino|first=Andy|title=[Andy Ristaino discusses the unicron tapestry]|url=http://www.formspring.me/skronked/q/392678438537806344|publisher=[[Spring.me|Spring.me]]|accessdate=April 18, 2013|date=November 13, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130703030345/http://www.formspring.me/skronked/q/392678438537806344|archivedate=2013年7月3日}}</ref> Later, in the DVD commentary for the fourth season, Herpich revealed that the unicorn is representative of the Lich, because they both have one horn.<ref name=tomlich>Herpich, Tom (Storyboard artist). 2014. "The Lich" [Commentary track], ''Adventure Time'' Season Four [DVD], Los Angeles, CA: [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]].</ref> The ending of the episode, featuring Farmworld Finn and a different animation style, had previously been foreshadowed in the earlier fourth season episode "King Worm".<ref name=jessemoy>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=Adventure Time Season 5|url=http://jessemoynihan.com/?p=1804|publisher=JesseMoynihan.com|accessdate=April 21, 2013|date=November 12, 2012|archive-date=2015-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416034529/http://jessemoynihan.com/?p=1804|dead-url=no}}</ref>

In the original storyboard for the episode, Billy was supposed to explain that he would push the Lich through the multiverse portal into the Crystal Citadel, a prison created so that no one can escape from it. Billy would further explain that the Citadel housed Finn's actual father. This rejected storyline would later be revisited at the end of the [[Adventure_Time_(season_5)|fifth season]]'s final episode "Billy's Bucket List", as well as the [[Adventure_Time_(season_6)|season six]] premiere "[[Wake_Up_(Adventure_Time)|Wake Up]]"/"[[Escape_from_the_Citadel|Escape from the Citadel]]". In the end of the episode, the Lich was originally supposed to try and convince Finn to give him the ''Enchiridon'' by promising that he could both bring back his birth parents and give him [[immortality|immortality]].<ref name=storyboard>{{cite web|last=Seibert|first=Fred|title='The Lich' Storyboard|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/112716702/The-Lich-Storyboard|publisher=[[Scribd|Scribd]]|accessdate=April 18, 2013|date=November 9, 2012|archive-date=2015-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416054927/https://www.scribd.com/doc/112716702/The-Lich-Storyboard|dead-url=no}}</ref> According to Ward, information regarding Finn's father was cut because it forced too much information in a short amount of time.<ref name=penlich>Ward, Pendleton (Series creator). 2014. "The Lich" [Commentary track], ''Adventure Time'' Season Four [DVD], Los Angeles, CA: [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]].</ref> Had this plot point stayed in the episode, Finn's father would have been portrayed as a hero.<ref name=tomlich/>

==Reception==
"The Lich" first aired on [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] on October 22, 2012. The episode was watched by 2.589 million viewers, and scored a 0.5 percent in the 18–49 demographic [[Nielsen_rating|Nielsen household rating]]; this means that it was seen by 0.5 percent of all 18–49 year-olds watching television at the time of the airing.<ref name=lichratings>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title=Monday Cable Ratings: 'Monday Night Football' Triumphs + Presidential Debate Ratings, 'On The Record', 'Monday Night RAW', 'SportsCenter' & More|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/23/monday-cable-ratings-monday-night-football-triumphs-presidential-debate-ratings-on-the-record-monday-night-raw-sportscenter-more/154273/|work=[[Television_Without_Pity|Television Without Pity]]|publisher=[[Zap2it|Zap2it]]|accessdate=October 25, 2012|date=October 23, 2012|archive-date=2012-10-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027150122/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/23/monday-cable-ratings-monday-night-football-triumphs-presidential-debate-ratings-on-the-record-monday-night-raw-sportscenter-more/154273/|dead-url=yes}}</ref> The episode first saw physical release as part of the complete fourth season DVD in October of 2014.<ref name=seasonfour>{{cite web|title=Cartoon Network-Adventure Time-Complete 4th Season|url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00KH57UXS|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.com]]|accessdate=June 27, 2014|date=June 27, 2014}}</ref> It was later re-released as part of the 2014 '' Finn the Human'' DVD, which included 16 episodes from the series' third, fourth, fifth, and sixth seasons.<ref name=finnthehumandvd>{{cite web|title=Adventure Time: Finn the Human 8|url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00MEXP5OW|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.com]]|accessdate=September 22, 2014|date=November 25, 2014|archive-date=2022-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220219233641/https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00MEXP5OW|dead-url=no}}</ref>

Oliver Sava of ''[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]'' was particularly pleased with the episode, and gave it an "A".<ref name=lichavclub/> He complimented the storyline, as well as the sequence featuring Finn and Jake stealing jewels, noting that it allowed "for increasingly bizarre visuals", such as Jake making a purse in his flesh to house the gems.<ref name=lichavclub/> Sava was particularly pleased with the ending, calling it "a doozy of a cliffhanger" as well as "the kind of ending that calls into question everything that we’ve seen before."<ref name=lichavclub>{{cite web|last=Sava|first=Oliver|title='The Lich' {{!}} Adventure Time {{!}} TV Club|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/lich,86689/|work=[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The_Onion|The Onion]]|accessdate=April 21, 2013|date=October 22, 2012|archive-date=2013-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030181138/http://www.avclub.com/articles/lich,86689/|dead-url=no}}</ref>
